      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "d78929cc6ef83ecd",
      "text": "Let's start with a simple distinction of forms of play: functional games, fantasy games, rule games.\nFunctional games (or practice games) emerge in the first months of life. After play-like body movements, especially with the mouth and hands, functional games with objects develop, such as rattle-let, drop-let, swim-let, and the first interaction games. In the alternation of hiding and coming out again (peek-a-boo game), the theme of hiding and breaking out of hiding is discovered, which then runs through the history of the game in an infinite number of variations.\n"
